<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06043d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06043d">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06043d"> 43(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> make me a good queen</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Telle est m&ecirc;me quelquefois la force de cette autoillusion chez l&apos;enfant qui, jouant, s&apos;est figur&eacute;, par exemple, &ecirc;tre un soldat, un matelot, un marchand, un cocher, un brigand ou un guide, que la m&eacute;tamorphose imaginaire persiste alors que le jeu a cess&eacute;. Sully rapporte qu&apos;un petit gar&ccedil;on de trois ans et demi aimait beaucoup jouer au charbonnier et continuait son r&ecirc;ve pendant toute la journ&eacute;e; ce jour-l&agrave;, non seulement il refusait d&apos;&ecirc;tre appel&eacute; de tout autre nom, mais il demandait dans sa pri&egrave;re: &ldquo;<mark>Fais que je sois un bon charbonnier</mark>&rdquo;, et non &ldquo;un bon gar&ccedil;on&rdquo;, comme d&apos;ordinaire &hellip;. <font color="green">[This is sometimes even the force of this self-illusion in the child who, playing, imagined himself, for example, to be a soldier, a sailor, a merchant, a coachman, a brigand or a guide, whom the imaginary metamorphosis persists then. that the game has stopped. Sully reports that a little boy of three and a half years was very fond of playing coalman and continued his dream all day long; that day, not only did he refuse to be called by any other name, but he asked in his prayer: &ldquo;Make me a good coalman&rdquo;, and not &ldquo;a good boy&rdquo;, as usual &hellip;]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 66</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
